04899nam a22007095i 9780226457017DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016033842  a9780226457017  a(DE-B1597)523211  a(OCoLC)988326284  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR905b.M37 2017 4aD16.14 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a907.2223  aHK 10712rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50102:1 aMcDowell, Paula, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Invention of the Oral :bPrint Commerce and Fugitive Voices in Eighteenth-Century Britain /cPaula McDowell. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b25 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Oral Tradition in the History of Mediation -- t2. Oral Tradition as A Tale of a Tub: Jonathan Swift’s Oratorial Machines -- t3. The Contagion of the Oral in A Journal of the Plague Year -- t4. Oratory Transactions: John “Orator” Henley and His Critics -- t5. How to Speak Well in Public: The Elocution Movement Begins in Earnest -- t6. “Fair Rhet'ric” and the Fishwives of Billingsgate -- t7. “The Art of Printing Was Fatal”: The Idea of Oral Tradition in Ballad Discourse -- t8. Conjecturing Oral Societies: Global to Gaelic -- tCoda: When Did “Orality” Become a “Culture”? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust as today’s embrace of the digital has sparked interest in the history of print culture, so in eighteenth-century Britain the dramatic proliferation of print gave rise to urgent efforts to historicize different media forms and to understand their unique powers. And so it was, Paula McDowell argues, that our modern concepts of oral culture and print culture began to crystallize, and authors and intellectuals drew on older theological notion of oral tradition to forge the modern secular notion of oral tradition that we know today. Drawing on an impressive array of sources including travel narratives, elocution manuals, theological writings, ballad collections, and legal records, McDowell re-creates a world in which everyone from fishwives to philosophers, clergymen to street hucksters, competed for space and audiences in taverns, marketplaces, and the street. She argues that the earliest positive efforts to theorize "oral tradition," and to depict popular oral culture as a culture (rather than a lack of culture), were prompted less by any protodemocratic impulse than by a profound discomfort with new cultures of reading, writing, and even speaking shaped by print. Challenging traditional models of oral versus literate societies and key assumptions about culture’s ties to the spoken and the written word, this landmark study reorients critical conversations across eighteenth-century studies, media and communications studies, the history of the book, and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aOral communicationzEngland. 0aOral historyzGreat BritainxSources. 0aOral traditionzEngland. 0aOral traditionzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPrintingzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aconcept formation.  afolk.  amedia history.  amedia shift.  aoral culture.  aoral tradition.  aorality.  aprint commerce.  aprint culture.  apublic sphere.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022645696640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226457017423Co